  "answer": "**No work in the Falsafa corpus matches this description.**\n\nExtensive searches across the English translations for key terms—including \"Amitābha\" with \"nostril\" or \"breath,\" \"Amoghasiddhi\" with \"left nostril,\" \"Ratnasambhava\" with \"breath,\" \"Akṣobhya\" with \"breath,\" \"Vairocana\" with \"breath\" or \"crown,\" the five Tathāgatas together, \"five tathagatas\" or \"five Tathāgatas,\" \"right nostril\" or \"left nostril,\" \"tip of the nose,\" \"forehead,\" \"crown of the head\" with Tathāgata references, \"Five Sacred Tastes,\" \"fivefold culmination,\" and \"stainless purity\" with breath—yielded zero relevant results.[^1]\n\nThe corpus contains 37 works, primarily Indic (Sanskrit/Kawi), philosophical, literary, and political texts, with some Buddhist or tantric-leaning Kawi works like *Kalpabuddha*, *San Hyan Kamahayanikan*, *Kunjarakarna Dharmakathana*, and *San Hyan Tattvajnana*. However, none discuss the five Dhyani Tathāgatas (Vairocana, Akṣobhya, Ratnasambhava, Amitābha, Amoghasiddhi) in connection with breath states, nostrils, or the specified phrases/locations. Hits on \"nostril\" or \"breath\" appear in Hindu (*Gaṇapatitattva*) or non-Buddhist contexts (e.g., planets in *San Hyan Tattvajnana*).\n\nThis specific Vajrayana/tantric breath-Tathāgata mapping (common in some Tibetan or Indo-Tibetan guhyamantra traditions) is not covered here.",
